\begin_layout Subsection
Classification of Appliances
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on our analysis of different appliances in common use, we have the
 following breakdown of appliances in terms of the kind of service they
 provide.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Physical presence is needed to receive the service from the appliance.
 Examples of appliances in this class include television, coffee machine,
 etc.
 Only persons within the vicinity of the appliance can benefit from it.
 This class includes appliances which may provide services to more than
 one user at the same time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Physical presence is not required to benefit from the appliance.
 Examples of appliances in this class include servers, networked printers,
 etc.
 Persons are able to receive service from these appliances without being
 present in the vicinity of the appliance.
 Typically this is done by logging into the appliance remotely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, there are certain appliances that cannot be characterized into
 either of the two classifications.
 These appliances provide a service regardless of the duration of time a
 user is interacting with it.
 Examples of appliances in this class include refrigerator, alarm clocks,
 etc.
 Regardless of the amount of times a person accesses these appliances, they
 are still providing a service to the user.
 The refrigerator by keeping the food cold and the alarm clock by maintaining
 the time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Accounting for energy consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most appliances can unambiguously be characterized into one of the three
 classes.
 Each class of appliances has a different policy for accounting for energy
 consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the class one appliances, consumption is determined by physical vicinity
 of the user to the appliance.
 The key contribution of our work is in measuring the consumption for these
 set of appliances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A number of policies can be used here.
 Based on the available information such as account logs, it can be determined
 who used which appliance for what period of time.
 Implementing this policy will require a per appliance implementation based
 on the type of logging an appliance if any it presents.
 Another policy to account for consumption here is to simply charge the
 owner or the operator of the appliance for the energy consumption.
 It is determined that there exists a relationship between the user and
 the owner of the appliance based on which the owner is allowing the user
 its use.
 This relationship may take a economic or a social personal form.
 Such a relationship can be determined for each appliance in this class.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The appliances in this class can be handled by an extension of class one
 appliances.
 The token system as introduced in section XX can be modified to issue indefinit
e tokens to all users of the appliances and the consumption will be split
 equally among them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limitations of the policies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are certain cases of energy consumption which we are unable to properly
 account for.
 Policy one can be stated as being around and being benefited.
 Policy two can be stated as not being around and being benefited.
 One policy case we cannot properly account for is being around and not
 being benefited.
 It is possible that a person is present in the vicinity of the appliance
 but not actually receiving any services from it.
 For example, a person maybe present in the vicinity of a television but
 not actually watching it.
 If the television is turned on, the person will be charged for it but the
 person is not actually benefiting from it.
 Presently, our system will claim that the person is actually benefiting
 from it as the person is inside the service range.
 This is a case of the pairing problem which is under research on a separate
 project in our lab [David Jea].
 We fail to account for this case and will over estimate the consumption
 of the user.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After classifying appliances into the different classes, we can construct
 an application that will monitor the energy consumption of the different
 classes of appliances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Application Description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We developed and deployed an application to estimate the consumption under
 the first classification of appliances.
 The third class of appliances and if the latter consumption policy for
 the second class of appliances is followed, they too can be monitored under
 this application with minor modifications.
 In the application, each user carries a RFID tag and each appliance is
 instrumented with a RFID reader and a power meter.
 The power meter records the energy consumption of the appliance and the
 RFID reader detects when a user enters the service range of the appliance.
 When a user is present in the service range of an appliance, the user is
 charged for the energy consumption of the appliance.
 If multiple users are present in the range, the charge is divided equally.
 The last person to leave the range will continue to be charged for the
 consumption of that appliance until another person enters the service range.
 We provide the ability for the users to observe their consumption in real-time
 through our Spotlight server.
 
