System Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design of the Spotlight system is centered around instrumentation of
 participating appliances.
 Each appliance is powered through a commercial-off-the-shelf power meter
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "wattsup"

\end_inset

 that measures the energy consumption for the appliance.
 The power meter provides a serial interface for external logging with a
 well documented serial protocol.
 This serial interface connects to a MICAz 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "micaz"

\end_inset

 'appliance' mote that forms the sensing and communication hub for the appliance.
 The power meter is configured to sense and report the power consumption
 at a 1 Hz sampling rate.
 Upon receiving power measurements from its UART, the appliance mote forwards
 these messages to the Spotlight server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MICAz mote is equipped with a 2.4 GHz radio that is used for sensing
 the physical vicinity of participating users as well as for communicating
 with the Spotlight server.
 Users carry MICAz 'tag' motes that send out periodic beacon messages advertisin
g their presence.
 The appliance motes listen for presence beacons and record the radio receive
 strength (RSSI) for any messages it receives.
 These RSSI values are also forwarded to the Spotlight server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Spotlight server is a system that receives beacon strengths and power
 measurements from the various appliance motes and processes them together
 to identify user vicinity and eventually per user appliance energy consumption.
 The Spotlight server is connected to the appliance motes through a 'base
 station' MICAz mote attached to the server's serial port.
 The Spotlight server uses the SensorBase 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "sensorbase.org"

\end_inset

 package to record, maintain and retrieve the measurements from the appliance
 motes.
 The SensorBase package not only provides a consistent interface to access
 the data but also gives fine grained privacy features that enable Spotlight
 users to protect their sensitive information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The software subsystems built into the appliance mote consist of the SOS
 operating system 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "sos05mobisys"

\end_inset

 with custom kernel and application modules that implement the serial protocol
 for the power meter and the active RFID reader.
 The tag motes run a stock version of the SOS kernel with a custom module
 for the vicinity beacons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Token System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To account for energy consumption, we introduce the notion of token and
 service range.
 As per the first classification of appliances, when a user is present within
 the service range of an appliance, the user is benefiting from it and the
 energy consumption of the appliance is accounted against that user.
 Further, to account for the scenario where a user may leave the vicinity
 of the appliance while it is still turned on, we introduce the notion of
 tokens.
 Energy consumption of users is counted against the tokens issued to the
 user.
 The policy for issuing and expiring tokens is following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Upon entering the service range of an appliance, the user is issued a token
 for the appliance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Upon exiting the service range of an appliance, if another user is present
 in the service range of the appliance, the token expires.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When a user enters the service range of an appliance, if there are any outstandi
ng tokens issued to users outside the service range, they expire.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Token-Issue"

\end_inset

 highlights this policy.
 The shaded area denotes the service range of the appliance.
 If a token is issued when a user is in the range or the token is expired
 when the user is outside the range, it is a valid outcome of the system.
 If a token expires inside the range or is issued outside the range, this
 is a false outcome of the system.
 Based on the token issue and expiry policy, energy consumption for users
 is accounted in the following manner.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The user with a token for an appliance is responsible for the energy consumed
 by that appliance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If more than one users hold a token to an appliance, the energy consumption
 is equally divided amongst them.
 
\end_layout

