\begin_layout Subsubsection
Further issues on Tokens
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the notion of the token is an abstraction for accounting energy consumptio
n of individuals, one could extend it.
 The extended token is a tuple associated with (Appliance ID, Type of energy,
 User ID, Time-out).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can imagine some other cases the token system cannot fairly distribute
 energy to users.
 And they can be resolved by doing this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
case (1) that a case where there are two users.
 After one uses an appliance intensively, then the other one came to the
 place and uses it for once.
 Imagine that the idle power consumption is almost the same as active power.
 Then the last one will unfairly be responsible for all the wasted energy
 until other one comes to the service range because the last ones token
 will not be expired for a long time.
 By giving them different types of tokens, one token for the active power,
 the other token for the idle power, the system can relatively fairly distribute
 energy to users.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
case (2) For the class III appliances, the system could issue tokens for
 affiliated users at the first time when an appliance starts working, and
 by never expiring the tokens users will be responsible for energy consumed
 by the appliances.
 The extended token, therefore, could enable users to set a policy for them
 to be fair.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "sub:Binary-detection-problem"

\end_inset

Binary detection and the token issuance problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two main issues that lead the token issuance problem hard.
 On one hand, RSSI suffers from significant variations over time and different
 devices.
 Lymberopoulos et.
 al.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "RSSI_yale"

\end_inset

 showed from their empirical study on RSSI variability in ZigBee radio that
 antenna orientation is a critical factor of its variability.
 Therefore, in case we cannot fix antenna orientation, the system should
 suffer from variable RSSI.
 Not only the antenna orientation, but also other factors, such as antenna
 and radio circuit characteristics, ambient attenuation characteristics,
 obstruction of Line-of-Sight and etc., render RSSI uncertain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the RSSI token space is uniform and signals and noises are
 well defined, one can see the token issuance algorithm is similar to the
 binary detection problem 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "binary_detection"

\end_inset

.
 Due to serious uncertainty of RSSI, however, it is challenging to define
 a mathematically tractable and reasonable binary detection model for it.
 So, we designed the detection problem from some observations of human behavior
 and RSSI characteristics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many attempts to make use of RSSI to localize mobile nodes.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "RSSI_local,RSSI_local2"

\end_inset

 give rough approximation of the relationship between distance and RSSI.
 Although the token space is roughly static and is definable in physical
 domain, the system's token algorithm is susceptible to a small noise when
 users are around the boundary of the service range.
 To avoid such case, we wanted to add hysteresis feature to the token issuance
 algorithm.
 Instead of having the same threshold value for both of issuance and expiration
 check routine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the comparison purpose in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Evaluation"

\end_inset

, in sum, we propose three detection techniques as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unified Threshold : An appliance has one RSSI based service range and issues/exp
ires a token whenever a user's RSSI is greater/less than the service range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calibrated Threshold : An appliance has a set of RSSI based service range
 for each RFID tag and issues/expires a token if a user's RSSI is greater/less
 than the tag specific service range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hysteresis Threshold : The same as the calibrated threshold, but set the
 expiration threshold as (calibrated threshold-hysteresis constant).
 
\end_layout

