\begin_layout Subsection
Evaluation of RSSI based token space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To confirm whether the RSSI based token issuance algorithm works, we measured
 the number of tokens issued at each point of predefined grids.
 Firstly, users define the service range of the appliances based upon physical
 vicinity information then draw rough boundaries.
 While users are walking along the boundaries with their RFID tags, the
 system averages RSSI for the initial calibration.
 After setting up the RSSI based service range, we made 30cm by 30cm grids
 over the house except the bathroom.
 And then with the calibrated RSSI service range, we tried to issue tokens
 for 5 times at each point, then counted number of issuance.
 Based on this numbers, we plot the contour maps of the token space.
 And in the figure yellow, red, green and blue colors give you the token
 space of the TV, the bedroom lamp, the living room lamp and the coffee
 machine, respectively.
 Because of the imperfection of RSSI values, we can see some outliers at
 (),(),(), and see some none uniform contours in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Measured-RSSI-Token"

\end_inset

.
 But, at the same time, it roughly gives us the real RSSI service range
 of the appliances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Measured-RSSI-Token"

\end_inset

, the token space is roughly static and is definable.
 The calibrated token issuance algorithm could be, however, susceptible
 to a small noise when users are around the boundaries of the service range.
 To avoid such case, we added hysteresis feature to the token issuance algorithm.
 Instead of having the same threshold value for both of issuance and expiration
 check routine (i.e.
 issuance threshold = -12, expiration threshold = -17).
 
\end_layout

